<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="28" type="female">
<paragraph pageId="17" pageNumber="28">Female.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="17" pageNumber="28">We associate females from French Guiana (Figs 13, 36), Peru, and Bolivia with this species. They have the same ventral wing pattern, a similar geographic range, and limited COI DNA sequences are the same.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="28" type="coi dna sequence">
<paragraph pageId="17" pageNumber="28">COI DNA sequence.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="17" pageNumber="28">
The sequence of a female from French Guiana (CF-LYC-039) is the same as (0% divergence) that of the male paratype from Peru (CF-LYC-020). This female is the first record of 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Lycaenidae" genus="Oenomaus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Oenomaus magnus" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="17" pageNumber="28" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="magnus">Oenomaus magnus</taxonomicName>
from French Guiana.
</paragraph>
